title: For Sale:  1944 Remington Rand m1911a1 in near perfect condition
postcontent:
I have a 1944 Remington Rany sd m1911a1 (serial 1377810) in near perfect condition.  I originally received this pistol from my grandparents, but have no family connections to the original owner.  The pistol was given to me in a US Graton & Knight Co. 1943 holster, which is in great condition for it's age.  Apparently these holsters were made specifically for the 1911, and were commonly used by soldiers during WWII.  The pistol is in great shape and fires perfectly.  The finish (parkerized) is also in excellent shape for it's age. The only thing that is not original is the magazine, which I have been told is nearly impossible to find a matching gun and mag because these were used in action, and often mags were discarded as they were used. 

Thanks,
Jacob

title: For Sale:  Rare Single Shot 98 Mauser Target rifle with Heavy Barrel in 223
postcontent:
This is a custom target rifle. It has a very heavy target barrel that I believe was a Douglas, but sadly I have misplaced the paperwork. It was built on a rare single-shot 98 Mauser action. This was not a rewelded commercial action, but a purpose built one that has never had a magazine and has three places where it connects to the floor plate through the stock. Standard 98 Mausers have two. It sits in a custom stock, but also comes with a partially finished stock as well. Attached to the front of the stock is a folding and extendable bipod. 

The scope sits on steel rings and is a 5-24x40 Tasco with dust covers. The trigger is an adjustable Mark-X trigger. As this is a single-shot target rifle, it has no safety, but you could install either a bolt shroud or a trigger that incorporates a safety. 

This rifle is HEAVY. It is in the neighborhood of 14lbs. It shoots like a 22lr with zero kick but obviously much further and flatter. 

When I got it I had the headspace checked and adjusted and in the process the holes that were drilled and tapped in the barrel were off-center. Instead of having the gunsmith turn down the barrel (potentially impacting accuracy) I had him install thread-in plugs which are visible. You could have the holes plugged, smoothed and polished into the barrel, thin and re-contour the barrel, or shoot it as is as I have done.
